# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: applied-mathematics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In mathematics, more specifically algebra, **abstract algebra** or **modern algebra** is the study of algebraic structures, which are sets with specific operations acting on their elements.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Algebraic structures include groups, rings, fields, modules, vector spaces, lattices, and algebras over a field.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The term *abstract algebra* was coined in the early 20th century to distinguish it from older parts of algebra, and more specifically from elementary algebra, the use of variables to represent numbers in computation and reasoning.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The abstract perspective on algebra has become so fundamental to advanced mathematics that it is simply called "algebra", while the term "abstract algebra" is seldom used except in pedagogy.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Algebraic structures, with their associated homomorphisms, form mathematical categories.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Category theory gives a unified framework to study properties and constructions that are similar for various structures.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Universal algebra is a related subject that studies types of algebraic structures as single objects.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] For example, the structure of groups is a single object in universal algebra, which is called the *variety of groups*.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Before the nineteenth century, algebra was defined as the study of polynomials.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Abstract algebra came into existence during the nineteenth century as more complex problems and solution methods developed.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Concrete problems and examples came from number theory, geometry, analysis, and the solutions of algebraic equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] This unification occurred in the early decades of the 20th century and resulted in the formal axiomatic definitions of various algebraic structures such as groups, rings, and fields.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] This historical development is almost the opposite of the treatment found in popular textbooks, such as van der Waerden's *Moderne Algebra*, which start each chapter with a formal definition of a structure and then follow it with concrete examples.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The study of polynomial equations or algebraic equations has a long history.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Circa 1700 BC, the Babylonians were able to solve quadratic equations specified as word problems.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] This word problem stage is classified as rhetorical algebra and was the dominant approach up to the 16th century.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Al-Khwarizmi originated the word "algebra" in 830 AD, but his work was entirely rhetorical algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Fully symbolic algebra did not appear until François Viète's 1591 New Algebra, and even this had some spelled out words that were given symbols in Descartes's 1637 *La Géométrie*.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The formal study of solving symbolic equations led Leonhard Euler to accept what were then considered "nonsense" roots such as negative numbers and imaginary numbers, in the late 18th century.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] However, European mathematicians, for the most part, resisted these concepts until the middle of the 19th century.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] George Peacock's 1830 *Treatise of Algebra* was the first attempt to place algebra on a strictly symbolic basis.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] He distinguished a new symbolical algebra, distinct from the old arithmetical algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Whereas in arithmetical algebra $a-b$ is restricted to $a\geq b$ , in symbolical algebra all rules of operations hold with no restrictions.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Using this Peacock could show laws such as $(-a)(-b)=ab$ , by letting $d=0,c=0$ in $(d-b)(c-a)=dc+ba-ad-bc$ .
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Peacock used what he termed the principle of the permanence of equivalent forms to justify his argument, but his reasoning suffered from the problem of induction.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] For example, ${\sqrt {a}}{\sqrt {b}}={\sqrt {ab}}$ holds for the nonnegative real numbers, but not for general complex numbers.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Several areas of mathematics led to the study of groups.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Lagrange's 1770 study of the solutions of the quintic equation led to the Galois group of a polynomial.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Gauss's 1801 study of Fermat's little theorem led to the ring of integers modulo n, the multiplicative group of integers modulo n, and the more general concepts of cyclic groups and abelian groups.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Klein's 1872 Erlangen program studied geometry and led to symmetry groups such as the Euclidean group and the group of projective transformations.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1874 Lie introduced the theory of Lie groups, aiming for "the Galois theory of differential equations".
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1876 Poincaré and Klein introduced the group of Möbius transformations, and its subgroups such as the modular group and Fuchsian group, based on work on automorphic functions in analysis.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The abstract concept of group emerged slowly over the middle of the nineteenth century.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Galois in 1832 was the first to use the term "group", signifying a collection of permutations closed under composition.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Arthur Cayley's 1854 paper *On the theory of groups* defined a group as a set with an associative composition operation and the identity 1, today called a monoid.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1870 Kronecker defined an abstract binary operation that was closed, commutative, associative, and had the left cancellation property $b\neq c\to a\cdot b\neq a\cdot c$ , similar to the modern laws for a finite abelian group.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Weber's 1882 definition of a group was a closed binary operation that was associative and had left and right cancellation.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Walther von Dyck in 1882 was the first to require inverse elements as part of the definition of a group.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Once this abstract group concept emerged, results were reformulated in this abstract setting.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] For example, Sylow's theorem was reproven by Frobenius in 1887 directly from the laws of a finite group, although Frobenius remarked that the theorem followed from Cauchy's theorem on permutation groups and the fact that every finite group is a subgroup of a permutation group.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Otto Hölder was particularly prolific in this area, defining quotient groups in 1889, group automorphisms in 1893, as well as simple groups.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] He also completed the Jordan–Hölder theorem.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Dedekind and Miller independently characterized Hamiltonian groups and introduced the notion of the commutator of two elements.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Burnside, Frobenius, and Molien created the representation theory of finite groups at the end of the nineteenth century.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] A. de Séguier's 1905 monograph *Elements of the Theory of Abstract Groups* presented many of these results in an abstract, general form, relegating "concrete" groups to an appendix, although it was limited to finite groups.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The first monograph on both finite and infinite abstract groups was O.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Schmidt's 1916 *Abstract Theory of Groups*.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Noncommutative ring theory began with extensions of the complex numbers to hypercomplex numbers, specifically William Rowan Hamilton's quaternions in 1843.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Many other number systems followed shortly.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1844, Hamilton presented biquaternions, Cayley introduced octonions, and Grassman introduced exterior algebras.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] James Cockle presented tessarines in 1848 and coquaternions in 1849.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] William Kingdon Clifford introduced split-biquaternions in 1873.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In addition Cayley introduced group algebras over the real and complex numbers in 1854 and square matrices in two papers of 1855 and 1858.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Once there were sufficient examples, it remained to classify them.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In an 1870 monograph, Benjamin Peirce classified the more than 150 hypercomplex number systems of dimension below 6, and gave an explicit definition of an associative algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] He defined nilpotent and idempotent elements and proved that any algebra contains one or the other.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] He also defined the Peirce decomposition.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Frobenius in 1878 and Charles Sanders Peirce in 1881 independently proved that the only finite-dimensional division algebras over $\mathbb {R}$ were the real numbers, the complex numbers, and the quaternions.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In the 1880s Killing and Cartan showed that semisimple Lie algebras could be decomposed into simple ones, and classified all simple Lie algebras.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Cartan was the first to define concepts such as direct sum and simple algebra, and these concepts proved quite influential.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1907 Wedderburn extended Cartan's results to an arbitrary field, in what are now called the Wedderburn principal theorem and Artin–Wedderburn theorem.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] For commutative rings, several areas together led to commutative ring theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In two papers in 1828 and 1832, Gauss formulated the Gaussian integers and showed that they form a unique factorization domain (UFD) and proved the biquadratic reciprocity law.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Jacobi and Eisenstein at around the same time proved a cubic reciprocity law for the Eisenstein integers.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The study of Fermat's Last Theorem led to the algebraic integers.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1847, Gabriel Lamé thought he had proven FLT, but his proof was faulty as he assumed all the cyclotomic fields were UFDs, yet as Kummer pointed out, $\mathbb {Q} (\zeta _{23}))$ was not a UFD.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1846 and 1847 Kummer introduced ideal numbers and proved unique factorization into ideal primes for cyclotomic fields.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Dedekind extended this in 1871 to show that every nonzero ideal in the domain of integers of an algebraic number field is a unique product of prime ideals, a precursor of the theory of Dedekind domains.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Overall, Dedekind's work created the subject of algebraic number theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In the 1850s, Riemann introduced the fundamental concept of a Riemann surface.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Riemann's methods relied on an assumption he called Dirichlet's principle, which in 1870 was questioned by Weierstrass.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Much later, in 1900, Hilbert justified Riemann's approach by developing the direct method in the calculus of variations.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In the 1860s and 1870s, Clebsch, Gordan, Brill, and especially M.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Noether studied algebraic functions and curves.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In particular, Noether studied what conditions were required for a polynomial to be an element of the ideal generated by two algebraic curves in the polynomial ring $\mathbb {R} [x,y]$ , although Noether did not use this modern language.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1882 Dedekind and Weber, in analogy with Dedekind's earlier work on algebraic number theory, created a theory of algebraic function fields which allowed the first rigorous definition of a Riemann surface and a rigorous proof of the Riemann–Roch theorem.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Kronecker in the 1880s, Hilbert in 1890, Lasker in 1905, and Macaulay in 1913 further investigated the ideals of polynomial rings implicit in E.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Lasker proved a special case of the Lasker-Noether theorem, namely that every ideal in a polynomial ring is a finite intersection of primary ideals.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Macaulay proved the uniqueness of this decomposition.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Overall, this work led to the development of algebraic geometry.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1801 Gauss introduced binary quadratic forms over the integers and defined their equivalence.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] He further defined the discriminant of these forms, which is an invariant of a binary form.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Between the 1860s and 1890s invariant theory developed and became a major field of algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Cayley, Sylvester, Gordan and others found the Jacobian and the Hessian for binary quartic forms and cubic forms.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1868 Gordan proved that the graded algebra of invariants of a binary form over the complex numbers was finitely generated, i.e., has a basis.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Hilbert wrote a thesis on invariants in 1885 and in 1890 showed that any form of any degree or number of variables has a basis.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] He extended this further in 1890 to Hilbert's basis theorem.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Once these theories had been developed, it was still several decades until an abstract ring concept emerged.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The first axiomatic definition was given by Abraham Fraenkel in 1914.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] His definition was mainly the standard axioms: a set with two operations addition, which forms a group (not necessarily commutative), and multiplication, which is associative, distributes over addition, and has an identity element.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In addition, he had two axioms on "regular elements" inspired by work on the p-adic numbers, which excluded now-common rings such as the ring of integers.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] These allowed Fraenkel to prove that addition was commutative.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Fraenkel's work aimed to transfer Steinitz's 1910 definition of fields over to rings, but it was not connected with the existing work on concrete systems.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Masazo Sono's 1917 definition was the first equivalent to the present one.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1920, Emmy Noether, in collaboration with W.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Schmeidler, published a paper about the theory of ideals in which they defined left and right ideals in a ring.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The following year she published a landmark paper called *Idealtheorie in Ringbereichen* (*Ideal theory in rings'*), analyzing ascending chain conditions with regard to (mathematical) ideals.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The publication gave rise to the term "Noetherian ring", and several other mathematical objects being called *Noetherian*.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Noted algebraist Irving Kaplansky called this work "revolutionary"; results which seemed inextricably connected to properties of polynomial rings were shown to follow from a single axiom.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Artin, inspired by Noether's work, came up with the descending chain condition.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] These definitions marked the birth of abstract ring theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1801 Gauss introduced the integers mod p, where p is a prime number.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Galois extended this in 1830 to finite fields with $p^{n}$ elements.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1871 Richard Dedekind introduced, for a set of real or complex numbers that is closed under the four arithmetic operations, the German word *Körper*, which means "body" or "corpus" (to suggest an organically closed entity).
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The English term "field" was introduced by Moore in 1893.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1881 Leopold Kronecker defined what he called a *domain of rationality*, which is a field of rational fractions in modern terms.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The first clear definition of an abstract field was due to Heinrich Martin Weber in 1893.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] It was missing the associative law for multiplication, but covered finite fields and the fields of algebraic number theory and algebraic geometry.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In 1910 Steinitz synthesized the knowledge of abstract field theory accumulated so far.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] He axiomatically defined fields with the modern definition, classified them by their characteristic, and proved many theorems commonly seen today.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The end of the 19th and the beginning of the 20th century saw a change in the methodology of mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Abstract algebra emerged around the start of the 20th century, under the name *modern algebra*.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Its study was part of the drive for more intellectual rigor in mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Initially, the assumptions in classical algebra, on which the whole of mathematics (and major parts of the natural sciences) depend, took the form of axiomatic systems.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] No longer satisfied with establishing properties of concrete objects, mathematicians started to turn their attention to general theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Formal definitions of certain algebraic structures began to emerge in the 19th century.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] For example, results about various groups of permutations came to be seen as instances of general theorems that concern a general notion of an *abstract group*.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Questions of structure and classification of various mathematical objects came to the forefront.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] These processes were occurring throughout all of mathematics but became especially noticeable in algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Formal definitions through primitive operations and axioms were proposed for many basic algebraic structures, such as groups, rings, and fields.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Hence such things as group theory and ring theory took their places in pure mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] By abstracting away various amounts of detail, mathematicians have defined various algebraic structures that are used in many areas of mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] For instance, almost all systems studied are sets, to which the theorems of set theory apply.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Those sets that have a certain binary operation defined on them form magmas, to which the concepts concerning magmas, as well those concerning sets, apply.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] We can add additional constraints on the algebraic structure, such as associativity (to form semigroups); identity, and inverses (to form groups); and other more complex structures.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] With additional structure, more theorems could be proved, but the generality is reduced.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In general there is a balance between the amount of generality and the richness of the theory: more general structures have usually fewer nontrivial theorems and fewer applications.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] A group is a set G together with a "group product", a binary operation $\cdot :G\times G\rightarrow G$ .
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] A ring is a set R with two binary operations, addition: $(x,y)\mapsto x+y,$ and multiplication: $(x,y)\mapsto xy$ satisfying the following axioms.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Because of its generality, abstract algebra is used in many fields of mathematics and science.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] For instance, algebraic topology uses algebraic objects to study topologies.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] The Poincaré conjecture, proved in 2003, asserts that the fundamental group of a manifold, which encodes information about connectedness, can be used to determine whether a manifold is a sphere or not.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Algebraic number theory studies various number rings that generalize the set of integers.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] Using tools of algebraic number theory, Andrew Wiles proved Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In physics, groups are used to represent symmetry operations, and the usage of group theory could simplify differential equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/abstract-algebra] In gauge theory, the requirement of local symmetry can be used to deduce the equations describing a system.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Actuaries are professionals trained in this discipline.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] In many countries, actuaries must demonstrate their competence by passing a series of rigorous professional examinations focused in fields such as probability and predictive analysis.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] News & World Report*, their job often has to do with using mathematics to identify risk so they can mitigate risk.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Actuarial science includes a number of interrelated subjects, including mathematics, probability theory, statistics, finance, economics, financial accounting and computer science.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Historically, actuarial science used deterministic models in the construction of tables and premiums.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] The science has gone through revolutionary changes since the 1980s due to the proliferation of high speed computers and the union of stochastic actuarial models with modern financial theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Many universities have undergraduate and graduate degree programs in actuarial science.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] In 2010, a study published by job search website CareerCast ranked actuary as the #1 job in the United States.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] The study used five key criteria to rank jobs: environment, income, employment outlook, physical demands, and stress.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] News & World Report* ranked actuary as the third-best job in the business sector and the eighth-best job in STEM.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Actuarial science became a formal mathematical discipline in the late 17th century with the increased demand for long-term insurance coverage such as burial, life insurance, and annuities.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] These long term coverages required that money be set aside to pay future benefits, such as annuity and death benefits many years into the future.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] This requires estimating future contingent events, such as the rates of mortality by age, as well as the development of mathematical techniques for discounting the value of funds set aside and invested.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] This led to the development of an important actuarial concept, referred to as the present value of a future sum.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Certain aspects of the actuarial methods for discounting pension funds have come under criticism from modern financial economics.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Actuarial science is also applied to property, casualty, liability, and general insurance.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] In these forms of insurance, coverage is generally provided on a renewable period (such as a yearly).
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Coverage can be cancelled at the end of the period by either party.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Property and casualty insurance companies tend to specialize because of the complexity and diversity of risks.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] One division is to organize around personal and commercial lines of insurance.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Personal lines of insurance are for individuals and include fire, auto, homeowners, theft, and umbrella coverages.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Commercial lines address the insurance needs of businesses and include property, business continuation, product liability, fleet/commercial vehicle, workers compensation, fidelity and surety, and D&O insurance.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] The insurance industry also provides coverage for exposures such as catastrophe, weather-related risks, earthquakes, patent infringement and other forms of corporate espionage, terrorism, and "one-of-a-kind" (e.g., satellite launch).
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Actuarial science provides data collection, measurement, estimating, forecasting, and valuation tools to provide financial and underwriting data for management to assess marketing opportunities and the nature of the risks.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Actuarial science often helps to assess the overall risk from catastrophic events in relation to its underwriting capacity or surplus.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] In the reinsurance fields, actuarial science can be used to design and price reinsurance and retrocession arrangements, and to establish reserve funds for known claims and future claims and catastrophes.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] There is an increasing trend to recognize that actuarial skills can be applied to a range of applications outside the traditional fields of insurance, pensions, etc.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] One notable example is the use in some US states of actuarial models to set criminal sentencing guidelines.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] These models attempt to predict the chance of re-offending according to rating factors which include the type of crime, age, educational background and ethnicity of the offender.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] However, these models have been open to criticism as providing justification for discrimination against specific ethnic groups by law enforcement personnel.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Whether this is statistically correct or a self-fulfilling correlation remains under debate.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Another example is the use of actuarial models to assess the risk of sex offense recidivism.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Actuarial models and associated tables, such as the MnSOST-R, Static-99, and SORAG, have been used since the late 1990s to determine the likelihood that a sex offender will re-offend and thus whether he or she should be institutionalized or set free.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Traditional actuarial science and modern financial economics in the US have different practices, which is caused by different ways of calculating funding and investment strategies, and by different regulations.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Historically, much of the foundation of actuarial theory predated modern financial theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] In the early twentieth century, actuaries were developing many techniques that can be found in modern financial theory, but for various historical reasons, these developments did not achieve much recognition.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] As a result, actuarial science developed along a different path, becoming more reliant on assumptions, as opposed to the arbitrage-free risk-neutral valuation concepts used in modern finance.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] The divergence is not related to the use of historical data and statistical projections of liability cash flows, but is instead caused by the manner in which traditional actuarial methods apply market data with those numbers.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] For example, one traditional actuarial method suggests that changing the mix of investments can change the value of liabilities and assets (by changing the discount rate assumption).
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] This concept is inconsistent with financial economics.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] The potential of modern financial economics theory to complement existing actuarial science was recognized by actuaries in the mid-twentieth century.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] In the late 1980s and early 1990s, there was a distinct effort for actuaries to combine financial theory and stochastic methods into their established models.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Ideas from financial economics became increasingly influential in actuarial thinking, and actuarial science has started to embrace more sophisticated mathematical modelling of finance.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Today, the profession, both in practice and in the educational syllabi of many actuarial organizations, is cognizant of the need to reflect the combined approach of tables, loss models, stochastic methods, and financial theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] However, assumption-dependent concepts are still widely used (such as the setting of the discount rate assumption as mentioned earlier), particularly in North America.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Product design adds another dimension to the debate.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Financial economists argue that pension benefits are bond-like and should not be funded with equity investments without reflecting the risks of not achieving expected returns.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] But some pension products do reflect the risks of unexpected returns.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] In some cases, the pension beneficiary assumes the risk, or the employer assumes the risk.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] 2. assets and liabilities with identical cash flows should have the same price.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] 3. the value of an asset is independent of its financing.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Essentially, financial economics state that pension assets should not be invested in equities for a variety of theoretical and practical reasons.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Elementary mutual aid agreements and pensions arose in antiquity.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Early in the Roman Empire, associations were formed to meet the expenses of burial, cremation, and monuments—precursors to burial insurance and friendly societies.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] A small sum was paid into a communal fund on a weekly basis, and upon the death of a member, the fund would cover the expenses of rites and burial.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] These societies sometimes sold shares in the building of columbāria, or burial vaults, owned by the fund—the precursor to mutual insurance companies.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Other early examples of mutual surety and assurance pacts can be traced back to various forms of fellowship within the Saxon clans of England and their Germanic forebears, and to Celtic society.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] However, many of these earlier forms of surety and aid would often fail due to lack of understanding and knowledge.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] The 17th century was a period of advances in mathematics in Germany, France and England.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] At the same time there was a rapidly growing desire and need to place the valuation of personal risk on a more scientific basis.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Independently of each other, compound interest was studied and probability theory emerged as a well-understood mathematical discipline.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Another important advance came in 1662 from a London draper, the father of demography, John Graunt, who showed that there were predictable patterns of longevity and death in a group, or cohort, of people of the same age, despite the uncertainty of the date of death of any one individual.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] This study became the basis for the original life table.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] One could now set up an insurance scheme to provide life insurance or pensions for a group of people, and to calculate with some degree of accuracy how much each person in the group should contribute to a common fund assumed to earn a fixed rate of interest.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] The first person to demonstrate publicly how this could be done was Edmond Halley (of Halley's Comet fame).
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Halley constructed his own life table, and showed how it could be used to calculate the premium amount someone of a given age should pay to purchase a life annuity.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] James Dodson's pioneering work on the long term insurance contracts under which the same premium is charged each year led to the formation of the Society for Equitable Assurances on Lives and Survivorship (now commonly known as Equitable Life) in London in 1762.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] William Morgan is often considered the father of modern actuarial science for his work in the field in the 1780s and 90s.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Many other life insurance companies and pension funds were created over the following 200 years.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Equitable Life was the first to use the word "actuary" for its chief executive officer in 1762.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Previously, "actuary" meant an official who recorded the decisions, or "acts", of ecclesiastical courts.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Other companies that did not use such mathematical and scientific methods most often failed or were forced to adopt the methods pioneered by Equitable.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] In the 18th and 19th centuries, calculations were performed without computers.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Actuarial organizations were founded to support and further both actuaries and actuarial science, and to protect the public interest by promoting competency and ethical standards.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] However, calculations remained cumbersome, and actuarial shortcuts were commonplace.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Non-life actuaries followed in the footsteps of their life insurance colleagues during the 20th century.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] The 1920 revision for the New-York based National Council on Workmen's Compensation Insurance rates took over two months of around-the-clock work by day and night teams of actuaries.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] In the 1930s and 1940s, the mathematical foundations for stochastic processes were developed.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] Actuaries could now begin to estimate losses using models of random events, instead of the deterministic methods they had used in the past.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] The introduction and development of the computer further revolutionized the actuarial profession.
[src:applied-mathematics/actuarial-science] From pencil-and-paper to punchcards to current high-speed devices, the modeling and forecasting ability of the actuary has rapidly improved while still being heavily dependent on the assumptions input into the models; actuaries have needed to adjust to this new world.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] "Aeronautical engineering" was the original term for the field.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] As flight technology advanced to include vehicles operating in outer space, the broader term "aerospace engineering" has come into use.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Aerospace engineering, particularly the astronautics branch, is often colloquially referred to as "rocket science".
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Flight vehicles are subjected to demanding conditions such as those caused by changes in atmospheric pressure and temperature, with structural loads applied upon vehicle components.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Consequently, they are usually the products of various technological and engineering disciplines including aerodynamics, air propulsion, avionics, materials science, structural analysis and manufacturing.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] The interaction between these technologies is known as aerospace engineering.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Because of the complexity and number of disciplines involved, aerospace engineering is carried out by teams of engineers, each having their own specialized area of expertise.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] The origin of aerospace engineering can be traced back to the aviation pioneers around the late 19th to early 20th centuries, although the work of Sir George Cayley dates from the last decade of the 18th to the mid-19th century.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] One of the most important people in the history of aeronautics and a pioneer in aeronautical engineering, Cayley is credited as the first person to separate the forces of lift and drag, which affect any atmospheric flight vehicle.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Early knowledge of aeronautical engineering was largely empirical, with some concepts and skills imported from other branches of engineering.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Some key elements, like fluid dynamics, were understood by 18th-century scientists.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] In December 1903, the Wright Brothers performed the first sustained, controlled flight of a powered, heavier-than-air aircraft, lasting 12 seconds.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] The 1910s saw the development of aeronautical engineering through the design of World War I military aircraft.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] In 1914, Robert Goddard was granted two U.S. patents for rockets using solid fuel, liquid fuel, multiple propellant charges, and multi-stage designs.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] This would set the stage for future applications in multi-stage propulsion systems for outer space.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Congress established the first aeronautical research administration, known as the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics, or NACA.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] It was the first government-sponsored organization to support aviation research.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Though intended as an advisory board upon inception, the Langley Aeronautical Laboratory became its first sponsored research and testing facility in 1920.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] The organization would later be redefined as NASA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Between World Wars I and II, great leaps were made in the field, accelerated by the advent of mainstream civil aviation.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Notable airplanes of this era include the Curtiss JN 4, Farman F.60 Goliath, and Fokker Trimotor.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Notable military airplanes of this period include the Mitsubishi A6M Zero, Supermarine Spitfire and Messerschmitt Bf 109 from Japan, United Kingdom, and Germany respectively.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] A significant development came with the first operational Jet engine-powered airplane, the Messerschmitt Me 262 which entered service in 1944 towards the end of the Second World War.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] The first definition of aerospace engineering appeared in February 1958, considering the Earth's atmosphere and outer space as a single realm, thereby encompassing both aircraft (*aero*) and spacecraft (*space*) under the newly coined term *aerospace*.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] In response to the USSR launching the first satellite, Sputnik, into space on October 4, 1957, U.S. aerospace engineers launched the first American satellite on January 31, 1958.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] The National Aeronautics and Space Administration was founded in 1958 after the Sputnik crisis.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] In 1969, Apollo 11, the first human space mission to land on the Moon, took place.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] It saw three astronauts enter orbit around the Moon, with two, Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin, visiting the lunar surface.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] The third astronaut, Michael Collins, stayed in orbit to rendezvous with Armstrong and Aldrin after their visit.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] An important innovation came on January 30, 1970, when the Boeing 747 made its first commercial flight from New York to London.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] This aircraft made history and became known as the "Jumbo Jet" or "Queen of the Skies" due to its ability to hold up to 480 passengers.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Another significant development came in 1976, with the development of the first passenger supersonic aircraft, the Concorde.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] The development of this aircraft was agreed upon by the French and British on November 29, 1962.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] On December 21, 1988, the Antonov An-225 *Mriya* cargo aircraft commenced its first flight.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] It holds the records for the world's heaviest aircraft, heaviest airlifted cargo, and longest airlifted cargo of any aircraft in operational service.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] On October 25, 2007, the Airbus A380 made its maiden commercial flight from Singapore to Sydney, Australia.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] This aircraft was the first passenger plane to surpass the Boeing 747 in terms of passenger capacity, with a maximum of 853.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Though development of this aircraft began in 1988 as a competitor to the 747, the A380 made its first test flight in April 2005.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] The basis of most of these elements lies in theoretical physics, such as fluid dynamics for aerodynamics or the equations of motion for flight dynamics.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] There is also a large empirical component.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Historically, this empirical component was derived from testing of scale models and prototypes, either in wind tunnels or in the free atmosphere.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] More recently, advances in computing have enabled the use of computational fluid dynamics to simulate the behavior of the fluid, reducing time and expense spent on wind-tunnel testing.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Those studying hydrodynamics or hydroacoustics often obtain degrees in aerospace engineering.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Aerospace engineering may be studied at the advanced diploma, bachelor's, master's, and Ph.D. levels in aerospace engineering departments at many universities, and in mechanical engineering departments at others.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] A few departments offer degrees in space-focused astronautical engineering.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Some institutions differentiate between aeronautical and astronautical engineering.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Graduate degrees are offered in advanced or specialty areas for the aerospace industry.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] A background in chemistry, physics, computer science and mathematics is important for students pursuing an aerospace engineering degree.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] The term "rocket scientist" is sometimes used to describe a person of great intelligence since rocket science is seen as a practice requiring great mental ability, especially technically and mathematically.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] The term is used ironically in the expression "It's not rocket science" to indicate that a task is simple.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] Strictly speaking, the use of "science" in "rocket science" is a misnomer since science is about understanding the origins, nature, and behavior of the universe; engineering is about using scientific and engineering principles to solve problems and develop new technology.
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] The more etymologically correct version of this phrase would be "rocket engineer".
[src:applied-mathematics/aerospace-engineering] However, "science" and "engineering" are often misused as synonyms.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In mathematics, **affine geometry** is what remains of Euclidean geometry when ignoring (mathematicians often say "forgetting") the metric notions of distance and angle.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] As the notion of *parallel lines* is one of the main properties that is independent of any metric, affine geometry is often considered as the study of parallel lines.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Therefore, Playfair's axiom (Given a line L and a point P not on L, there is exactly one line parallel to L that passes through P.) is fundamental in affine geometry.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Comparisons of figures in affine geometry are made with affine transformations, which are mappings that preserve alignment of points and parallelism of lines.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Affine geometry can be developed in two ways that are essentially equivalent.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In synthetic geometry, an affine space is a set of *points* to which is associated a set of lines, which satisfy some axioms (such as Playfair's axiom).
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Affine geometry can also be developed on the basis of linear algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] By choosing any point as "origin", the points are in one-to-one correspondence with the vectors, but there is no preferred choice for the origin; thus an affine space may be viewed as obtained from its associated vector space by "forgetting" the origin (zero vector).
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] The idea of forgetting the metric can be applied in the theory of manifolds.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] That is developed in the article *Affine connection*.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In 1748, Leonhard Euler introduced the term *affine* (from Latin *affinis* 'related') in his book *Introductio in analysin infinitorum* (volume 2, chapter XVIII).
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In 1827, August Möbius wrote on affine geometry in his *Der barycentrische Calcul* (chapter 3).
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] After Felix Klein's Erlangen program, affine geometry was recognized as a generalization of Euclidean geometry.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In 1918, Hermann Weyl referred to affine geometry for his text *Space, Time, Matter*.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] He used affine geometry to introduce vector addition and subtraction at the earliest stages of his development of mathematical physics.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] of light-signals in four-dimensional space-time.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] ; then the parallel transport in question is such that it carries any null-vector at one point into the position of a null-vector at a neighboring point.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] The various types of affine geometry correspond to what interpretation is taken for *rotation*.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Euclidean geometry corresponds to the ordinary idea of rotation, while Minkowski's geometry corresponds to hyperbolic rotation.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] With respect to perpendicular lines, they remain perpendicular when the plane is subjected to ordinary rotation.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In the Minkowski geometry, lines that are hyperbolic-orthogonal remain in that relation when the plane is subjected to hyperbolic rotation.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] (Desargues) Given seven distinct points A, A', B, B', C, C', O, such that AA', BB', CC' are distinct lines through O, and AB is parallel to A'B', and BC is parallel to B'C', then AC is parallel to A'C'.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] The affine concept of parallelism forms an equivalence relation on lines.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Since the axioms of ordered geometry as presented here include properties that imply the structure of the real numbers, those properties carry over here so that this is an axiomatization of affine geometry over the field of real numbers.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] The first non-Desarguesian plane was noted by David Hilbert in his *Foundations of Geometry*.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] The Moulton plane is a standard illustration.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In order to provide a context for such geometry as well as those where Desargues theorem is valid, the concept of a ternary ring was developed by Marshall Hall.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In this approach affine planes are constructed from ordered pairs taken from a ternary ring.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] A plane is said to have the "minor affine Desargues property" when two triangles in parallel perspective, having two parallel sides, must also have the third sides parallel.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] If this property holds in the affine plane defined by a ternary ring, then there is an equivalence relation between "vectors" defined by pairs of points from the plane.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Geometrically, affine transformations (affinities) preserve collinearity: so they transform parallel lines into parallel lines and preserve ratios of distances along parallel lines.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] We identify as *affine theorems* any geometric result that is invariant under the affine group (in Felix Klein's Erlangen programme this is its underlying group of symmetry transformations for affine geometry).
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Consider in a vector space V, the general linear group GL(*V*).
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] It is not the whole *affine group* because we must allow also translations by vectors v in V.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] For example, the theorem from the plane geometry of triangles about the concurrence of the lines joining each vertex to the midpoint of the opposite side (at the *centroid* or *barycenter*) depends on the notions of *mid-point* and *centroid* as affine invariants.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Other examples include the theorems of Ceva and Menelaus.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Affine invariants can also assist calculations.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] For example, the lines that divide the area of a triangle into two equal halves form an envelope inside the triangle.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] The ratio of the area of the envelope to the area of the triangle is affine invariant, and so only needs to be calculated from a simple case such as a unit isosceles right angled triangle to give ${\tfrac {3}{4}}\log _{e}(2)-{\tfrac {1}{2}},$ i.e.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Familiar formulas such as half the base times the height for the area of a triangle, or a third the base times the height for the volume of a pyramid, are likewise affine invariants.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] While the latter is less obvious than the former for the general case, it is easily seen for the one-sixth of the unit cube formed by a face (area 1) and the midpoint of the cube (height 1/2).
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Hence it holds for all pyramids, even slanting ones whose apex is not directly above the center of the base, and those with base a parallelogram instead of a square.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] The formula further generalizes to pyramids whose base can be dissected into parallelograms, including cones by allowing infinitely many parallelograms (with due attention to convergence).
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] The same approach shows that a four-dimensional pyramid has 4D hypervolume one quarter the 3D volume of its parallelepiped base times the height, and so on for higher dimensions.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Two types of affine transformation are used in kinematics, both classical and modern.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Velocity *v* is described using length and direction, where length is presumed unbounded.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] This variety of kinematics, styled as Galilean or Newtonian, uses coordinates of absolute space and time.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] The shear mapping of a plane with an axis for each represents coordinate change for an observer moving with velocity *v* in a resting frame of reference.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Finite light speed, first noted by the delay in appearance of the moons of Jupiter, requires a modern kinematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] The method involves rapidity instead of velocity, and substitutes squeeze mapping for the shear mapping used earlier.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] This affine geometry was developed synthetically in 1912. to express the special theory of relativity.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In 1984, "the affine plane associated to the Lorentzian vector space *L*2" was described by Graciela Birman and Katsumi Nomizu in an article entitled "Trigonometry in Lorentzian geometry".
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Affine geometry can be viewed as the geometry of an affine space of a given dimension *n*, coordinatized over a field *K*.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] There is also (in two dimensions) a combinatorial generalization of coordinatized affine space, as developed in synthetic finite geometry.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In projective geometry, *affine space* means the complement of a hyperplane at infinity in a projective space.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] *Affine space* can also be viewed as a vector space whose operations are limited to those linear combinations whose coefficients sum to one, for example 2*x* − *y*, *x* − *y* + *z*, (*x* + *y* + *z*)/3, **i***x* + (1 − **i**)*y*, etc.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Synthetically, affine planes are 2-dimensional affine geometries defined in terms of the relations between points and lines (or sometimes, in higher dimensions, hyperplanes).
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Defining affine (and projective) geometries as configurations of points and lines (or hyperplanes) instead of using coordinates, one gets examples with no coordinate fields.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] A major property is that all such examples have dimension 2.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Finite examples in dimension 2 (finite affine planes) have been valuable in the study of configurations in infinite affine spaces, in group theory, and in combinatorics.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Despite being less general than the configurational approach, the other approaches discussed have been very successful in illuminating the parts of geometry that are related to symmetry.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In traditional geometry, affine geometry is considered to be a study between Euclidean geometry and projective geometry.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] On the one hand, affine geometry is Euclidean geometry with congruence left out; on the other hand, affine geometry may be obtained from projective geometry by the designation of a particular line or plane to represent the points at infinity.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In affine geometry, there is no metric structure but the parallel postulate does hold.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] Affine geometry provides the basis for Euclidean structure when perpendicular lines are defined, or the basis for Minkowski geometry through the notion of hyperbolic orthogonality.
[src:applied-mathematics/affine-geometry] In this viewpoint, an affine transformation is a projective transformation that does not permute finite points with points at infinity, and affine transformation geometry is the study of geometrical properties through the action of the group of affine transformations.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Lyapunov is known for his development of the stability theory of a dynamical system, as well as for his many contributions to mathematical physics and probability theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Lyapunov was born in Yaroslavl, Russian Empire.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] His father Mikhail Vasilyevich Lyapunov (1820–1868) was an astronomer employed by the Demidov Lyceum.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] His brother, Sergei Lyapunov, was a gifted composer and pianist.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Lyapunov retired from his scientific career and relocated his family to his wife's estate at Bolobonov, in the Simbirsk province (now Ulyanovsk Oblast).
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] After the death of his father in 1868, Aleksandr Lyapunov was educated by his uncle R.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Sechenov, brother of the physiologist Ivan Mikhailovich Sechenov.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] At his uncle's family, Lyapunov studied with his distant cousin Natalia Rafailovna, who became his wife in 1886.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] In 1870, his mother moved with her sons to Nizhny Novgorod, where he started the third class of the gymnasium.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] He graduated from the gymnasium with distinction in 1876.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] In 1876, Lyapunov entered the Physico-Mathematical department at the University of Saint Petersburg, but after one month he transferred to the Mathematics department of the university.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Among the Saint Petersburg mathematics professors were Chebyshev and his students Aleksandr Nikolaevich Korkin and Yegor Ivanovich Zolotarev.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Lyapunov wrote his first independent scientific works under the guidance of the professor of mechanics, D.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] In 1880 Lyapunov received a gold medal for a work on hydrostatics.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] This was the basis for his first published scientific works *On the equilibrium of a heavy body in a heavy fluid contained in a vessel of a fixed form* and *On the potential of hydrostatic pressure*.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Lyapunov also completed his university course in 1880, two years after Andrey Markov who had also graduated at Saint Petersburg University.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Lyapunov maintained scientific contact with Markov throughout his life.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] A major theme in Lyapunov's research was the stability of a rotating fluid mass with possible astronomical application.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] This subject was proposed to Lyapunov by Chebyshev as a topic for his masters thesis which he submitted in 1884 with the title *On the stability of ellipsoidal forms of rotating fluids*.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] The main contribution was published in the celebrated monograph 'A.M.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Lyapunov, The general problem of the stability of motion.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Kharkov Mathematical Society, Kharkov, 251p.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] This led on to his 1892 doctoral thesis *The general problem of the stability of motion*.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] The thesis was defended in Moscow University on 12 September 1892, with Nikolai Zhukovsky and V.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] In 1908, the Kharkov edition was translated to French and republished by the University of Toulouse: 'Probleme General de la Stabilite du Mouvement, Par M.A.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] In 1885, Lyapunov became privatdozent and was proposed to accept the chair of mechanics at Kharkov University, where he went the same year.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] His student and collaborator, Vladimir Steklov, recalled his first lecture in the following way: "A handsome young man, almost of the age of the other students, came before the audience, where there was also the old Dean, professor Levakovsky, who was respected by all students.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] After the Dean had left, the young man with a trembled voice started to lecture a course on the dynamics of material points, instead of a course on dynamical systems.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] This subject was already known to the students from the lectures of professor Delarue.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] But what Lyapunov taught us was new to me and I had never seen this material in any textbook.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] All antipathy to the course was immediately blown to dust.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Lyapunov returned to Saint Petersburg in 1902, after being elected acting member of the Academy of Science as well as ordinary professor in the Faculty of Applied Mathematics of the university.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] The position had been left vacant by the death of his former teacher, Chebyshev.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Not having any teaching obligations, this allowed Lyapunov to focus on his studies and in particular he was able to bring to a conclusion the work on the problem of Chebyshev with which he started his scientific career.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] In 1908, he took part to the Fourth International Mathematical Congress in Rome.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] He also participated in the publication of Euler's selected works: he was an editor of the volumes 18 and 19.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] By the end of June 1917, Lyapunov traveled with his wife to his brother's palace in Odessa.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Lyapunov's wife was suffering from tuberculosis so they moved in accordance with her doctor's orders.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] The same day, Lyapunov shot himself in the head, and three days later he died.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] By that time, he was going blind from cataracts.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Lyapunov contributed to several fields, including differential equations, potential theory, dynamical systems and probability theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] His main preoccupations were the stability of equilibria and the motion of mechanical systems, especially rotating fluid masses, and the study of particles under the influence of gravity.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] His work in the field of mathematical physics regarded the boundary value problem of the equation of Laplace.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] In the theory of potential, his work from 1897 *On some questions connected with Dirichlet's problem* clarified several important aspects of the theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] His work in this field is in close connection with the work of Steklov.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Lyapunov developed many important approximation methods.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] His methods, which he developed in 1899, make it possible to define the stability of sets of ordinary differential equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] He created the modern theory of the stability of a dynamical system.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] In the theory of probability, he generalized the works of Chebyshev and Markov, and proved the Central Limit Theorem under more general conditions than his predecessors.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] The method of characteristic functions he used for the proof later found widespread use in probability theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Like many mathematicians, Lyapunov preferred to work alone and communicated mainly with few colleagues and close relatives.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] He usually worked late, four to five hours at night, sometimes the whole night.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] Once or twice a year he visited the theatre, or went to some concert.
[src:applied-mathematics/aleksandr-lyapunov] He was an honorary member of many universities, an honorary member of the academy in Rome and a corresponding member of the Academy of Sciences in Paris.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] Although, recent research has adopted the name "APS" as a synonym for Cl3,0(**R**) in general contexts.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The APS can be used to construct a compact, unified, and geometrical formalism for both classical and quantum mechanics.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] This blurs the line between what is traditionally considered classical or quantum.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The APS should not be confused with spacetime algebra (STA), which concerns the Clifford algebra Cl1,3(**R**) of the four-dimensional Minkowski spacetime.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] All Clifford or geometric algebras have three main involutions: grade involution, reversion, and Clifford conjugation.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The notation for grade involution in the APS is not a settled matter, and is also denoted by ${\hat {g}}$ or ${\overline {g}}^{\dagger }$ .
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The above tilde notation is more recent and was adopted to emphasize this relationship.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] Throughout the remainder of this article and unless stated otherwise, units such that *c* = 1 are used, called natural units.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] In the Pauli matrix representation, the unit basis vectors are replaced by the Pauli matrices and the scalar part by the identity matrix.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] In the matrix representation, the Lorentz rotor is seen to form an instance of the SL(2, **C**) group (special linear group of degree 2 over the complex numbers), which is the double cover of the Lorentz group.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The unitary element *R* is called a rotor because this encodes rotations, and the Hermitian element *L* encodes boosts.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The total object $\Lambda$ is called a **Lorentz rotor**.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The proper velocity transforms under the action of the Lorentz rotor $\Lambda$ as $u\rightarrow u^{\prime }=\Lambda u\Lambda ^{\dagger }.$ This transformation law can be easily derived from the isomorphism between the APS and the even subalgebra of the STA.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The electromagnetic field is represented as a bi-paravector *F*: $F=\mathbf {E} +i\mathbf {B} ,$ where the Hermitian part gives the electric field *E*, the anti-Hermitian part gives the magnetic field *B*, and $i=\mathbf {e} _{1}\mathbf {e} _{2}\mathbf {e} _{3}$ is the unit pseudoscalar.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The source of the field *F* is the electromagnetic four-current: $J=\rho +\mathbf {J} \,,$ where the scalar part equals the electric charge density *ρ*, and the vector part the electric current density **J**.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] Introducing the electromagnetic potential paravector defined as: $A=\phi +\mathbf {A} \,,$ in which the scalar part equals the electric potential *ϕ*, and the vector part the magnetic potential **A**.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The electromagnetic field is then also: $F=\partial {\widetilde {A}}.$ The field can be split into electric $E=\langle \partial {\widetilde {A}}\rangle _{1}$ and magnetic $B=i\langle \partial {\widetilde {A}}\rangle _{2}$ components.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] Here, $\partial =\partial _{t}+\mathbf {e} _{1}\,\partial _{x}+\mathbf {e} _{2}\,\partial _{y}+\mathbf {e} _{3}\,\partial _{z}$ and *F* is invariant under a gauge transformation of the form $A\rightarrow A+\partial \chi \,,$ where $\chi$ is a scalar field.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The electromagnetic field is covariant under Lorentz transformations according to the law $F\rightarrow F^{\prime }=\Lambda F{\widetilde {\Lambda }}\,.$ This transformation law can be easily derived from the isomorphism between the APS and the even subalgebra of the STA.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The electromagnetic Lagrangian is $L={\frac {1}{2}}\langle FF\rangle _{0\oplus 3}-\langle A{\widetilde {J}}\rangle _{0\oplus 3}\,,$ which is a real scalar invariant.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra-of-physical-space] The electromagnetic interaction has been included via minimal coupling in terms of the potential *A*.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] studies which values solve equations formed using arithmetical operations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Elementary algebra is the main form of algebra taught in schools.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It examines mathematical statements using variables for unspecified values and seeks to determine for which values the statements are true.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] To do so, it uses different methods of transforming equations to isolate variables.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Linear algebra is a closely related field that investigates linear equations and combinations of them called *systems of linear equations*.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It provides methods to find the values that solve all equations in the system at the same time, and to study the set of these solutions.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Abstract algebra studies algebraic structures, which consist of a set of mathematical objects together with one or several operations defined on that set.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It is a generalization of elementary and linear algebra since it allows mathematical objects other than numbers and non-arithmetic operations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It distinguishes between different types of algebraic structures, such as groups, rings, and fields, based on the number of operations they use and the laws they follow, called axioms.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Universal algebra and category theory provide general frameworks to investigate abstract patterns that characterize different classes of algebraic structures.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebraic methods were first studied in the ancient period to solve specific problems in fields like geometry.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] This changed in the 9th century with Muḥammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī, who systematized algebra as an independent mathematical discipline, distinct from geometry.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Early mathematicians described equations and their solutions using words and abbreviations until the 16th and 17th centuries, when a rigorous symbolic formalism was developed.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In the mid-19th century, the scope of algebra broadened beyond a theory of equations to cover diverse types of algebraic operations and structures.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebra is relevant to many branches of mathematics, such as geometry, topology, number theory, and calculus, and other fields of inquiry, like logic and the empirical sciences.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebra is the branch of mathematics that studies algebraic structures and the operations they use.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] An algebraic structure is a non-empty set of mathematical objects, such as the integers, together with algebraic operations defined on that set, like addition and multiplication.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebra explores the laws, general characteristics, and types of algebraic structures.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Within certain algebraic structures, it examines the use of variables in equations and how to manipulate these equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebra is often understood as a generalization of arithmetic.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Arithmetic studies operations like addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division, in a particular domain of numbers, such as the real numbers.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Elementary algebra constitutes the first level of abstraction.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Like arithmetic, it restricts itself to specific types of numbers and operations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It generalizes these operations by allowing indefinite quantities in the form of variables in addition to numbers.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A higher level of abstraction is found in abstract algebra, which is not limited to a particular domain and examines algebraic structures such as groups and rings.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It extends beyond typical arithmetic operations by also covering other types of operations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Universal algebra is still more abstract in that it is not interested in specific algebraic structures but investigates the characteristics of algebraic structures in general.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The term *algebra* is sometimes used in a more narrow sense to refer only to elementary algebra or only to abstract algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] When used as a countable noun, an algebra is a specific type of algebraic structure that involves a vector space equipped with a certain type of binary operation, a bilinear map.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Depending on the context, "algebra" can also refer to other algebraic structures, like a Lie algebra or an associative algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The word *algebra* comes from the Arabic term الجبر (*al-jabr*), which originally referred to the surgical treatment of bonesetting.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The word entered the English language in the 16th century from Italian, Spanish, and medieval Latin.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Initially, its meaning was restricted to the theory of equations, that is, to the art of manipulating polynomial equations in view of solving them.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] This changed in the 19th century when the scope of algebra broadened to cover the study of diverse types of algebraic operations and structures together with their underlying axioms, the laws they follow.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Elementary algebra, also called school algebra, college algebra, and classical algebra, is the oldest and most basic form of algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It is a generalization of arithmetic that relies on variables and examines how mathematical statements may be transformed.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Arithmetic is the study of numerical operations and investigates how numbers are combined and transformed using the arithmetic operations of addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, exponentiation, extraction of roots, and logarithm.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, the operation of addition combines two numbers, called the addends, into a third number, called the sum, as in $2+5=7$ .
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Elementary algebra relies on the same operations while allowing variables in addition to regular numbers.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Variables are symbols for unspecified or unknown quantities.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] They make it possible to state relationships for which one does not know the exact values and to express general laws that are true, independent of which numbers are used.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, the equation $2\times 3=3\times 2$ belongs to arithmetic and expresses an equality only for these specific numbers.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] By replacing the numbers with variables, it is possible to express a general law that applies to any possible combination of numbers, like the commutative property of multiplication, which is expressed in the equation $a\times b=b\times a$ .
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebraic expressions are formed by using arithmetic operations to combine variables and numbers.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] By convention, the lowercase letters ⁠ x ⁠, ⁠ y ⁠, and z represent variables.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In some cases, subscripts are added to distinguish variables, as in ⁠ $x_{1}$ ⁠, ⁠ $x_{2}$ ⁠, and ⁠ $x_{3}$ ⁠.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The lowercase letters ⁠ a ⁠, ⁠ b ⁠, and c are usually used for constants and coefficients.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The expression $5x+3$ is an algebraic expression created by multiplying the number 5 with the variable x and adding the number 3 to the result.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Some algebraic expressions take the form of statements that relate two expressions to one another.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] An equation is a statement formed by comparing two expressions, saying that they are equal.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] This can be expressed using the equals sign (⁠ = ⁠), as in ⁠ $5x^{2}+6x=3y+4$ ⁠.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Inequations involve a different type of comparison, saying that the two sides are different.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] This can be expressed using symbols such as the less-than sign (⁠ < ⁠), the greater-than sign (⁠ > ⁠), and the inequality sign (⁠ $\neq$ ⁠).
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Unlike other expressions, statements can be true or false, and their truth value usually depends on the values of the variables.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, the statement $x^{2}=4$ is true if x is either 2 or −2 and false otherwise.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Equations with variables can be divided into identity equations and conditional equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Identity equations are true for all values that can be assigned to the variables, such as the equation ⁠ $2x+5x=7x$ ⁠.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Conditional equations are only true for some values.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, the equation $x+4=9$ is only true if x is 5.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The main goal of elementary algebra is to determine the values for which a statement is true.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] This can be achieved by transforming and manipulating statements according to certain rules.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A key principle guiding this process is that whatever operation is applied to one side of an equation also needs to be done to the other side.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, if one subtracts 5 from the left side of an equation one also needs to subtract 5 from the right side to balance both sides.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The goal of these steps is usually to isolate the variable one is interested in on one side, a process known as solving the equation for that variable.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, the equation $x-7=4$ can be solved for x by adding 7 to both sides, which isolates x on the left side and results in the equation ⁠ $x=11$ ⁠.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] There are many other techniques used to solve equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Simplification is employed to replace a complicated expression with an equivalent simpler one.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, the expression $7x-3x$ can be replaced with the expression $4x$ since $7x-3x=(7-3)x=4x$ by the distributive property.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For statements with several variables, substitution is a common technique to replace one variable with an equivalent expression that does not use this variable.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, if one knows that $y=3x$ then one can simplify the expression $7xy$ to arrive at ⁠ $21x^{2}$ ⁠.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In a similar way, if one knows the value of one variable one may be able to use it to determine the value of other variables.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebraic equations can be interpreted geometrically to describe spatial figures in the form of a graph.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] To do so, the different variables in the equation are understood as coordinates and the values that solve the equation are interpreted as points of a graph.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, if x is set to zero in the equation ⁠ $y=0.5x-1$ ⁠, then y must be −1 for the equation to be true.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] This means that the $(x,y)$ -pair $(0,-1)$ is part of the graph of the equation.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The $(x,y)$ -pair ⁠ $(0,7)$ ⁠, by contrast, does not solve the equation and is therefore not part of the graph.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The graph encompasses the totality of $(x,y)$ -pairs that solve the equation.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A polynomial is an expression consisting of one or more terms that are added or subtracted from each other, like ⁠ $x^{4}+3xy^{2}+5x^{3}-1$ ⁠.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Each term is either a constant, a variable, or a product of a constant and variables.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Each variable can be raised to a positive integer power.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A monomial is a polynomial with one term while two- and three-term polynomials are called binomials and trinomials.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The degree of a polynomial is the maximal value (among its terms) of the sum of the exponents of the variables (4 in the above example).
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Polynomials of degree one are called *linear polynomials*.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Linear algebra studies systems of linear polynomials.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A polynomial is said to be *univariate* or *multivariate*, depending on whether it uses one or more variables.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Factorization is a method used to simplify polynomials, making it easier to analyze them and determine the values for which they evaluate to zero.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Factorization consists of rewriting a polynomial as a product of several factors.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The polynomial as a whole is zero if and only if one of its factors is zero, i.e., if x is either −2 or 5.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Before the 19th century, much of algebra was devoted to polynomial equations, that is equations obtained by equating a polynomial to zero.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The first attempts for solving polynomial equations were to express the solutions in terms of nth roots.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Solutions for the degrees 3 and 4 are given by the cubic and quartic formulas.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] There are no general solutions for higher degrees, as proven in the 19th century by the Abel–Ruffini theorem.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Even when general solutions do not exist, approximate solutions can be found by numerical tools like the Newton–Raphson method.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The fundamental theorem of algebra asserts that every univariate polynomial equation of positive degree with real or complex coefficients has at least one complex solution.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Consequently, every polynomial of a positive degree can be factorized into linear polynomials.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] This theorem was proved at the beginning of the 19th century, but this does not close the problem since the theorem does not provide any way for computing the solutions.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Linear algebra starts with the study of systems of linear equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A *system of linear equations* is a set of linear equations for which one is interested in common solutions.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Matrices are rectangular arrays of values that have been originally introduced for having a compact and synthetic notation for systems of linear equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Under some conditions on the number of rows and columns, matrices can be added, multiplied, and sometimes inverted.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] All methods for solving linear systems may be expressed as matrix manipulations using these operations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, solving the above system consists of computing an inverted matrix $A^{-1}$ such that $A^{-1}A=I,$ where I is the identity matrix.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Methods of solving systems of linear equations range from the introductory, like substitution and elimination, to more advanced techniques using matrices, such as Cramer's rule, the Gaussian elimination, and LU decomposition.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Some systems of equations are inconsistent, meaning that no solutions exist because the equations contradict each other.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Consistent systems have either one unique solution or an infinite number of solutions.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The study of vector spaces and linear maps form a large part of linear algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A vector space is an algebraic structure formed by a set with an addition that makes it an abelian group and a scalar multiplication that is compatible with addition (see vector space for details).
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A linear map is a function between vector spaces that is compatible with addition and scalar multiplication.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In the case of finite-dimensional vector spaces, vectors and linear maps can be represented by matrices.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It follows that the theories of matrices and finite-dimensional vector spaces are essentially the same.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In particular, vector spaces provide a third way for expressing and manipulating systems of linear equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] From this perspective, a matrix is a representation of a linear map: if one chooses a particular basis to describe the vectors being transformed, then the entries in the matrix give the results of applying the linear map to the basis vectors.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Systems of equations can be interpreted as geometric figures.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For systems with two variables, each equation represents a line in two-dimensional space.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The point where the two lines intersect is the solution of the full system because this is the only point that solves both the first and the second equation.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For inconsistent systems, the two lines run parallel, meaning that there is no solution since they never intersect.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] If two equations are not independent then they describe the same line, meaning that every solution of one equation is also a solution of the other equation.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] These relations make it possible to seek solutions graphically by plotting the equations and determining where they intersect.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The same principles also apply to systems of equations with more variables, with the difference being that the equations do not describe lines but higher dimensional figures.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For instance, equations with three variables correspond to planes in three-dimensional space, and the points where all planes intersect solve the system of equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Abstract algebra, also called modern algebra, is the study of algebraic structures.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] An algebraic structure is a framework for understanding operations on mathematical objects, like the addition of numbers.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] While elementary algebra and linear algebra work within the confines of particular algebraic structures, abstract algebra takes a more general approach that compares how algebraic structures differ from each other and what types of algebraic structures there are, such as groups, rings, and fields.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The key difference between these types of algebraic structures lies in the number of operations they use and the laws they obey.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In mathematics education, abstract algebra refers to an advanced undergraduate course that mathematics majors take after completing courses in linear algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] On a formal level, an algebraic structure is a set of mathematical objects, called the underlying set, together with one or several operations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Abstract algebra is primarily interested in binary operations, which take any two objects from the underlying set as inputs and maps them to another object from this set as output.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, the algebraic structure $\langle \mathbb {N} ,+\rangle$ has the natural numbers (⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠) as the underlying set and addition (⁠ + ⁠) as its binary operation.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The underlying set can contain mathematical objects other than numbers, and the operations are not restricted to regular arithmetic operations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For instance, the underlying set of the symmetry group of a geometric object is made up of geometric transformations, such as rotations, under which the object remains unchanged.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Its binary operation is function composition, which takes two transformations as input and has the transformation resulting from applying the first transformation followed by the second as its output.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Abstract algebra classifies algebraic structures based on the laws or axioms that its operations obey and the number of operations it uses.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] One of the most basic types is a group, which has one operation and requires that this operation is associative and has an identity element and inverse elements.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] An operation is associative if the order of several applications does not matter, i.e., if $(a\circ b)\circ c$ is the same as $a\circ (b\circ c)$ for all elements.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] An operation has an identity element or a neutral element if one element *e* exists that does not change the value of any other element, i.e., if ⁠ $a\circ e=e\circ a=a$ ⁠.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] An operation has inverse elements if for any element a there exists a reciprocal element $a^{-1}$ that undoes ⁠ a ⁠.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] If an element operates on its inverse then the result is the neutral element *e*, expressed formally as ⁠ $a\circ a^{-1}=a^{-1}\circ a=e$ ⁠.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Every algebraic structure that fulfills these requirements is a group.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, $\langle \mathbb {Z} ,+\rangle$ is a group formed by the set of integers together with the operation of addition.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The neutral element is 0 and the inverse element of any number a is $-a$ .
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The natural numbers with addition, by contrast, do not form a group since they contain only positive integers and therefore lack inverse elements.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Group theory examines the nature of groups, with basic theorems such as the fundamental theorem of finite abelian groups and the Feit–Thompson theorem.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The latter was a key early step in one of the most important mathematical achievements of the 20th century: the collaborative effort, taking up more than 10,000 journal pages and mostly published between 1960 and 2004, that culminated in a complete classification of finite simple groups.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A ring is an algebraic structure with two operations that work similarly to the addition and multiplication of numbers and are named and generally denoted similarly.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A ring is a commutative group under addition: the addition of the ring is associative, commutative, and has an identity element and inverse elements.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The multiplication is associative and distributive with respect to addition; that is, $a(b+c)=ab+ac$ and $(b+c)a=ba+ca.$ Moreover, multiplication is associative and has an identity element generally denoted as 1.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Multiplication needs not to be commutative; if it is commutative, one has a commutative ring.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The ring of integers (⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠) is one of the simplest commutative rings.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A *field* is a commutative ring such that ⁠ $1\neq 0$ ⁠ and each nonzero element has a multiplicative inverse.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The ring of integers does not form a field because it lacks multiplicative inverses.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, the multiplicative inverse of 7 is ⁠ ${\tfrac {1}{7}}$ ⁠, which is not an integer.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The rational numbers, the real numbers, and the complex numbers each form a field with the operations of addition and multiplication.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Ring theory is the study of rings, exploring concepts such as subrings, quotient rings, polynomial rings, and ideals as well as theorems such as Hilbert's basis theorem.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Field theory is concerned with fields, examining field extensions, algebraic closures, and finite fields.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Galois theory explores the relation between field theory and group theory, relying on the fundamental theorem of Galois theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Besides groups, rings, and fields, there are many other algebraic structures studied by algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] They include magmas, semigroups, monoids, abelian groups, commutative rings, modules, lattices, vector spaces, algebras over a field, and associative and non-associative algebras.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] They differ from each other regarding the types of objects they describe and the requirements that their operations fulfill.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Many are related to each other in that a basic structure can be turned into a more specialized structure by adding constraints.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, a magma becomes a semigroup if its operation is associative.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Homomorphisms are tools to examine structural features by comparing two algebraic structures.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A homomorphism is a function from the underlying set of one algebraic structure to the underlying set of another algebraic structure that preserves certain structural characteristics.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] If the two algebraic structures use binary operations and have the form $\langle A,\circ \rangle$ and $\langle B,\star \rangle$ then the function $h:A\to B$ is a homomorphism if it fulfills the following requirement: ⁠ $h(x\circ y)=h(x)\star h(y)$ ⁠.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The existence of a homomorphism reveals that the operation $\star$ in the second algebraic structure plays the same role as the operation $\circ$ does in the first algebraic structure.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Isomorphisms are a special type of homomorphism that indicates a high degree of similarity between two algebraic structures.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] An isomorphism is a bijective homomorphism, meaning that it establishes a one-to-one relationship between the elements of the two algebraic structures.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] This implies that every element of the first algebraic structure is mapped to one unique element in the second structure without any unmapped elements in the second structure.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Another tool of comparison is the relation between an algebraic structure and its subalgebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The algebraic structure and its subalgebra use the same operations, which follow the same axioms.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The only difference is that the underlying set of the subalgebra is a subset of the underlying set of the algebraic structure.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] All operations in the subalgebra are required to be closed in its underlying set, meaning that they only produce elements that belong to this set.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, the set of even integers together with addition is a subalgebra of the full set of integers together with addition.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] This is the case because the sum of two even numbers is again an even number.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] But the set of odd integers together with addition is not a subalgebra because it is not closed: adding two odd numbers produces an even number, which is not part of the chosen subset.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Universal algebra is the study of algebraic structures in general.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] As part of its general perspective, it is not concerned with the specific elements that make up the underlying sets and considers operations with more than two inputs, such as ternary operations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It provides a framework for investigating what structural features different algebraic structures have in common.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] One of those structural features concerns the identities that are true in different algebraic structures.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In this context, an identity is a universal equation or an equation that is true for all elements of the underlying set.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, commutativity is a universal equation that states that $a\circ b$ is identical to $b\circ a$ for all elements.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A variety is a class of all algebraic structures that satisfy certain identities.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, if two algebraic structures satisfy commutativity then they are both part of the corresponding variety.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Category theory examines how mathematical objects are related to each other using the concept of categories.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] A category is a collection of objects together with a collection of morphisms or "arrows" between those objects.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] These two collections must satisfy certain conditions.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, morphisms can be joined, or *composed*: if there exists a morphism from object a to object ⁠ b ⁠, and another morphism from object b to object ⁠ c ⁠, then there must also exist one from object a to object ⁠ c ⁠.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Composition of morphisms is required to be associative, and there must be an "identity morphism" for every object.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Categories are widely used in contemporary mathematics since they provide a unifying framework to describe and analyze many fundamental mathematical concepts.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, sets can be described with the category of sets, and any group can be regarded as the morphisms of a category with just one object.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The origin of algebra lies in attempts to solve mathematical problems involving arithmetic calculations and unknown quantities.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] These developments happened in the ancient period in Babylonia, Egypt, Greece, China, and India.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] One of the earliest documents on algebraic problems is the Rhind Mathematical Papyrus from ancient Egypt, which was written around 1650 BCE.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It discusses solutions to linear equations, as expressed in problems like "A quantity; its fourth is added to it.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] What is the quantity?" Babylonian clay tablets from around the same time explain methods to solve linear and quadratic polynomial equations, such as the method of completing the square.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Many of these insights found their way to the ancient Greeks.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Starting in the 6th century BCE, their main interest was geometry rather than algebra, but they employed algebraic methods to solve geometric problems.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, they studied geometric figures while taking their lengths and areas as unknown quantities to be determined, as exemplified in Pythagoras' formulation of the difference of two squares method and later in Euclid's *Elements*.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In the 3rd century CE, Diophantus provided a detailed treatment of how to solve algebraic equations in a series of books called *Arithmetica*.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] He was the first to experiment with symbolic notation to express polynomials.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Diophantus's work influenced Arab development of algebra, with many of his methods reflected in the concepts and techniques used in medieval Arabic algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In ancient China, *The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art*, a book composed over the period spanning from the 10th century BCE to the 2nd century CE, explored various techniques for solving algebraic equations, including the use of matrix-like constructs.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It is disputed whether these early developments are part of algebra or only precursors.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] They offered solutions to algebraic problems but did not conceive them in an abstract and general manner, focusing instead on specific cases and applications.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] This changed with the Persian mathematician Al-Khwarizmi, who published his *The Compendious Book on Calculation by Completion and Balancing* in 825 CE.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Al-Khwarizmi provided the first analytical theory for solving equations by classifying them into six standard forms and offering systematic, step-by-step procedures for their solutions.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] By abstracting these methods from specific geometric figures and treating unknown quantities as general algebraic objects, he established a formal operational framework.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] This transition from solving isolated problems to developing a universal methodology transformed algebra into a self-contained discipline.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Other influential contributions to algebra came from the Arab mathematician Thābit ibn Qurra also in the 9th century and the Persian mathematician Omar Khayyam in the 11th and 12th centuries.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In India, Brahmagupta investigated how to solve quadratic equations and systems of equations with several variables in the 7th century CE.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Among his innovations were the use of zero and negative numbers in algebraic equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The Indian mathematicians Mahāvīra in the 9th century and Bhāskara II in the 12th century further refined Brahmagupta's methods and concepts.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In 1247, the Chinese mathematician Qin Jiushao wrote the *Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections*, which includes an algorithm for the numerical evaluation of polynomials, including polynomials of higher degrees.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] invented a symbolic notation to express equations in an abstract and concise manner.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The Italian mathematician Fibonacci brought al-Khwarizmi's ideas and techniques to Europe in books including his *Liber Abaci*.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In 1545, the Italian polymath Gerolamo Cardano published his book *Ars Magna*, which covered many topics in algebra, discussed imaginary numbers, and was the first to present general methods for solving cubic and quartic equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In the 16th and 17th centuries, the French mathematicians François Viète and René Descartes introduced letters and symbols to denote variables and operations, making it possible to express equations in a concise and abstract manner.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Their predecessors had relied on verbal descriptions of problems and solutions.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Some historians see this development as a key turning point in the history of algebra and consider what came before it as the prehistory of algebra because it lacked the abstract nature based on symbolic manipulation.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In the 17th and 18th centuries, many attempts were made to find general solutions to polynomials of degree five and higher.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] At the end of the 18th century, the German mathematician Carl Friedrich Gauss proved the fundamental theorem of algebra, which describes the existence of zeros of polynomials of any degree without providing a general solution.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] At the beginning of the 19th century, the Italian mathematician Paolo Ruffini and the Norwegian mathematician Niels Henrik Abel were able to show that no general solution exists for polynomials of degree five and higher.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In response to and shortly after their findings, the French mathematician Évariste Galois developed what came later to be known as Galois theory, which offered a more in-depth analysis of the solutions of polynomials while also laying the foundation of group theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Mathematicians soon realized the relevance of group theory to other fields and applied it to disciplines like geometry and number theory.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Starting in the mid-19th century, interest in algebra shifted from the study of polynomials associated with elementary algebra towards a more general inquiry into algebraic structures, marking the emergence of abstract algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] This approach explored the axiomatic basis of arbitrary algebraic operations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The invention of new algebraic systems based on different operations and elements accompanied this development, such as Boolean algebra, vector algebra, and matrix algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Influential early developments in abstract algebra were made by the German mathematicians David Hilbert, Ernst Steinitz, and Emmy Noether as well as the Austrian mathematician Emil Artin.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] They researched different forms of algebraic structures and categorized them based on their underlying axioms into types, like groups, rings, and fields.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The idea of the even more general approach associated with universal algebra was conceived by the English mathematician Alfred North Whitehead in his 1898 book *A Treatise on Universal Algebra*.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Starting in the 1930s, the American mathematician Garrett Birkhoff expanded these ideas and developed many of the foundational concepts of this field.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The invention of universal algebra led to the emergence of various new areas focused on the algebraization of mathematics—that is, the application of algebraic methods to other branches of mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Topological algebra arose in the early 20th century, studying algebraic structures such as topological groups and Lie groups.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] In the 1940s and 50s, homological algebra emerged, employing algebraic techniques to study homology.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Around the same time, category theory was developed and has since played a key role in the foundations of mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Other developments were the formulation of model theory and the study of free algebras.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The influence of algebra is wide-reaching, both within mathematics and in its applications to other fields.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The algebraization of mathematics is the process of applying algebraic methods and principles to other branches of mathematics, such as geometry, topology, number theory, and calculus.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It happens by employing symbols in the form of variables to express mathematical insights on a more general level, allowing mathematicians to develop formal models describing how objects interact and relate to each other.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] One application, found in geometry, is the use of algebraic statements to describe geometric figures.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, the equation $y=3x-7$ describes a line in two-dimensional space while the equation $x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}=1$ corresponds to a sphere in three-dimensional space.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Of special interest to algebraic geometry are algebraic varieties, which are solutions to systems of polynomial equations that can be used to describe more complex geometric figures.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebraic reasoning can also solve geometric problems.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, one can determine whether and where the line described by $y=x+1$ intersects with the circle described by $x^{2}+y^{2}=25$ by solving the system of equations made up of these two equations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Topology studies the properties of geometric figures or topological spaces that are preserved under operations of continuous deformation.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebraic topology relies on algebraic theories such as group theory to classify topological spaces.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, homotopy groups classify topological spaces based on the existence of loops or holes in them.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Number theory is concerned with the properties of and relations between integers.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebraic number theory applies algebraic methods and principles to this field of inquiry.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Examples are the use of algebraic expressions to describe general laws, like Fermat's Last Theorem, and of algebraic structures to analyze the behavior of numbers, such as the ring of integers.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The related field of combinatorics uses algebraic techniques to solve problems related to counting, arrangement, and combination of discrete objects.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] An example in algebraic combinatorics is the application of group theory to analyze graphs and symmetries.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The insights of algebra are also relevant to calculus, which uses mathematical expressions to examine rates of change and accumulation.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It relies on algebra, for instance, to understand how these expressions can be transformed and what role variables play in them.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebraic logic employs the methods of algebra to describe and analyze the structures and patterns that underlie logical reasoning, exploring both the relevant mathematical structures themselves and their application to concrete problems of logic.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It includes the study of Boolean algebra to describe propositional logic as well as the formulation and analysis of algebraic structures corresponding to more complex systems of logic.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebraic methods are also commonly employed in other areas, like the natural sciences.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, they are used to express scientific laws and solve equations in physics, chemistry, and biology.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Similar applications are found in fields like economics, geography, engineering (including electronics and robotics), and computer science to express relationships, solve problems, and model systems.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Linear algebra plays a central role in artificial intelligence and machine learning, for instance, by enabling the efficient processing and analysis of large datasets.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Various fields rely on algebraic structures investigated by abstract algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, physical sciences like crystallography and quantum mechanics make extensive use of group theory, which is also employed to study puzzles such as Sudoku and Rubik's Cubes, and origami.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Both coding theory and cryptology rely on abstract algebra to solve problems associated with data transmission, like avoiding the effects of noise and ensuring data security.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Algebra education mostly focuses on elementary algebra, which is one of the reasons why elementary algebra is also called school algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It is usually not introduced until secondary education since it requires mastery of the fundamentals of arithmetic while posing new cognitive challenges associated with abstract reasoning and generalization.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] It aims to familiarize students with the formal side of mathematics by helping them understand mathematical symbolism, for example, how variables can be used to represent unknown quantities.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] An additional difficulty for students lies in the fact that, unlike arithmetic calculations, algebraic expressions are often difficult to solve directly.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Instead, students need to learn how to transform them according to certain laws, often to determine an unknown quantity.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Some tools to introduce students to the abstract side of algebra rely on concrete models and visualizations of equations, including geometric analogies, manipulatives including sticks or cups, and "function machines" representing equations as flow diagrams.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] One method uses balance scales as a pictorial approach to help students grasp basic problems of algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The mass of some objects on the scale is unknown and represents variables.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Solving an equation corresponds to adding and removing objects on both sides in such a way that the sides stay in balance until the only object remaining on one side is the object of unknown mass.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Word problems are another tool to show how algebra is applied to real-life situations.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] For example, students may be presented with a situation in which Naomi's brother has twice as many apples as Naomi.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Given that both together have twelve apples, students are then asked to find an algebraic equation that describes this situation (⁠ $2x+x=12$ ⁠) and to determine how many apples Naomi has (⁠ $x=4$ ⁠).
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] At the university level, mathematics students encounter advanced algebra topics from linear and abstract algebra.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Initial undergraduate courses in linear algebra focus on matrices, vector spaces, and linear maps.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] Upon completing them, students are usually introduced to abstract algebra, where they learn about algebraic structures like groups, rings, and fields, as well as the relations between them.
[src:applied-mathematics/algebra] The curriculum typically also covers specific instances of algebraic structures, such as the systems of rational numbers, the real numbers, and the polynomials.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] In the past, practical applications have motivated the development of mathematical theories, which then became the subject of study in pure mathematics where abstract concepts are studied for their own sake.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] The activity of applied mathematics is thus intimately connected with research in pure mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Historically, applied mathematics consisted principally of applied analysis, most notably differential equations; approximation theory (broadly construed, to include representations, asymptotic methods, variational methods, and numerical analysis); and applied probability.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] These areas of mathematics related directly to the development of Newtonian physics, and in fact, the distinction between mathematicians and physicists was not sharply drawn before the mid-19th century.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Engineering and computer science departments have traditionally made use of applied mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Today, the term "applied mathematics" is used in a broader sense.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] It includes the classical areas noted above as well as other areas that have become increasingly important in applications.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Even fields such as number theory that are part of pure mathematics are now important in applications (such as cryptography), though they are not generally considered to be part of the field of applied mathematics *per se*.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] There is no consensus as to what the various branches of applied mathematics are.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Such categorizations are made difficult by the way mathematics and science change over time, and also by the way universities organize departments, courses, and degrees.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Many mathematicians distinguish between "applied mathematics", which is concerned with mathematical methods, and the "applications of mathematics" within science and engineering.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] A biologist using a population model and applying known mathematics would not be *doing* applied mathematics, but rather *using* it; however, mathematical biologists have posed problems that have stimulated the growth of pure mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Mathematicians such as Poincaré and Arnold deny the existence of "applied mathematics" and claim that there are only "applications of mathematics." Similarly, non-mathematicians blend applied mathematics and applications of mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] The use and development of mathematics to solve industrial problems is also called "industrial mathematics".
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] These are often considered interdisciplinary.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Sometimes, the term **applicable mathematics** is used to distinguish between the traditional applied mathematics that developed alongside physics and the many areas of mathematics that are applicable to real-world problems today, although there is no consensus as to a precise definition.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Mathematicians often distinguish between "applied mathematics" on the one hand, and the "applications of mathematics" or "applicable mathematics" both within and outside of science and engineering, on the other.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Some mathematicians emphasize the term applicable mathematics to separate or delineate the traditional applied areas from new applications arising from fields that were previously seen as pure mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] For example, from this viewpoint, an ecologist or geographer using population models and applying known mathematics would not be doing applied, but rather applicable, mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Other authors prefer describing *applicable mathematics* as a union of "new" mathematical applications with the traditional fields of applied mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] With this outlook, the terms applied mathematics and applicable mathematics are thus interchangeable.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Historically, mathematics was most important in the natural sciences and engineering.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] However, since World War II, fields outside the physical sciences have spawned the creation of new areas of mathematics, such as game theory and social choice theory, which grew out of economic considerations.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Further, the utilization and development of mathematical methods expanded into other areas leading to the creation of new fields such as mathematical finance and data science.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Statistics is probably the most widespread mathematical science used in the social sciences.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Academic institutions are not consistent in the way they group and label courses, programs, and degrees in applied mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] At some schools, there is a single mathematics department, whereas others have separate departments for Applied Mathematics and (Pure) Mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] It is very common for Statistics departments to be separated at schools with graduate programs, but many undergraduate-only institutions include statistics under the mathematics department.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Many applied mathematics programs (as opposed to departments) consist primarily of cross-listed courses and jointly appointed faculty in departments representing applications.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Some Ph.D. programs in applied mathematics require little or no coursework outside mathematics, while others require substantial coursework in a specific area of application.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] In some respects this difference reflects the distinction between "application of mathematics" and "applied mathematics".
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Some universities in the U.K. host departments of *Applied Mathematics and Theoretical Physics*, but it is now much less common to have separate departments of pure and applied mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] A notable exception to this is the Department of Applied Mathematics and Theoretical Physics at the University of Cambridge, housing the Lucasian Professor of Mathematics whose past holders include Isaac Newton, Charles Babbage, James Lighthill, Paul Dirac, and Stephen Hawking.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Schools with separate applied mathematics departments range from Brown University, which has a large Division of Applied Mathematics that offers degrees through the doctorate, to Santa Clara University, which offers only the M.S. in applied mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Research universities dividing their mathematics department into pure and applied sections include MIT.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Students in this program also learn another skill (computer science, engineering, physics, pure math, etc.) to supplement their applied math skills.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Mathematics is used in all branches of engineering and has subsequently developed as distinct specialties within the engineering profession.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] For example, continuum mechanics is foundational to civil, Mechanical engineering and aerospace engineering, with courses in solid mechanics and fluid mechanics being important components of the engineering curriculum.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Continuum mechanics is also an important branch of mathematics in its own right.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] It has served as the inspiration for a vast range of difficult research questions for mathematicians involved in the analysis of partial differential equations, differential geometry and the calculus of variations.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Perhaps the most well-known mathematical problem posed by a continuum mechanical system is the question of Navier-Stokes existence and smoothness.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Prominent career mathematicians rather than engineers who have contributed to the mathematics of continuum mechanics are Clifford Truesdell, Walter Noll, Andrey Kolmogorov and George Batchelor.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] An essential discipline for many fields in engineering is that of control engineering.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] The associated mathematical theory of this specialism is control theory, a branch of applied mathematics that builds off the mathematics of dynamical systems.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Control theory has played a significant enabling role in modern technology, serving a foundational role in electrical, mechanical and aerospace engineering.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Like continuum mechanics, control theory has also become a field of mathematical research in its own right, with mathematicians such as Aleksandr Lyapunov, Norbert Wiener, Lev Pontryagin and Fields Medal recipient Pierre-Louis Lions contributing to its foundations.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Scientific computing includes applied mathematics (especially numerical analysis), computing science (especially high-performance computing), and mathematical modelling in a scientific discipline.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Computer science relies on logic, algebra, discrete mathematics such as graph theory, and combinatorics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Operations research and management science are often taught in faculties of engineering, business, and public policy.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Applied mathematics has substantial overlap with the discipline of statistics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Statistical theorists study and improve statistical procedures with mathematics, and statistical research often raises mathematical questions.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Statistical theory relies on probability and decision theory, and makes extensive use of scientific computing, analysis, and optimization; for the design of experiments, statisticians use algebra and combinatorial design.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Applied mathematicians and statisticians often work in a department of mathematical sciences (particularly at colleges and small universities).
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Actuarial science applies probability, statistics, and economic theory to assess risk in insurance, finance and other industries and professions.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Mathematical economics is the application of mathematical methods to represent theories and analyze problems in economics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] The applied methods usually refer to nontrivial mathematical techniques or approaches.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Mathematical economics is based on statistics, probability, mathematical programming (as well as other computational methods), operations research, game theory, and some methods from mathematical analysis.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] In this regard, it resembles (but is distinct from) financial mathematics, another part of applied mathematics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] with MSC2010 classifications for 'Game theory' at codes 91Axx Archived 2015-04-02 at the Wayback Machine and for 'Mathematical economics' at codes 91Bxx Archived 2015-04-02 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] The line between applied mathematics and specific areas of application is often blurred.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] Many universities teach mathematical and statistical courses outside the respective departments, in departments and areas including business, engineering, physics, chemistry, psychology, biology, computer science, scientific computation, information theory, and mathematical physics.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] The Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics is an international applied mathematics organization.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] As of 2024, the society has 14,000 individual members.
[src:applied-mathematics/applied-mathematics] The American Mathematics Society has its Applied Mathematics Group.
